SIMPLE: son
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Son
<hw>Son</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sone</ets>,
<ets>sune</ets>, AS. <ets>sunu</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zoon</ets>, OS.,
OFries., & OHG. <ets>sunu</ets>, G. <ets>sohn</ets>, Icel.
<ets>sonr</ets>, Sw. <ets>son</ets>, Dan. <ets>s⟦oum⟧n</ets>, Goth.
<ets>sunus</ets>, Lith. <ets>sunus</ets>, Russ. <ets>suin'</ets>, Skr.
<ets>s⟦umac⟧nu</ets> (from <ets>s⟦umac⟧</ets> to beget, to bear), and
Gr. <?/ son. ⟦root⟧293. Cf. <er>Sow</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A male child; the male issue, or offspring, of a
parent, father or mother.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sarah conceived, and bare Abraham a <qex>son</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xxi. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A male descendant, however distant; hence, in the
plural, descendants in general.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am the <qex>son</qex> of the wise, the <qex>son</qex> of ancient
kings.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xix. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am the Lord, I change not; therefore ye <qex>sons</qex> of Jacob
are not consumed.</q> <rj><qau>Mal. iii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any young male person spoken of as a child; an
adopted male child; a pupil, ward, or any other young male
dependent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The child grew, and she brought him unto Pharaoh's daughter, and
he became her <qex>son</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. ii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be plain, good <qex>son</qex>, and homely in thy drift.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of some specified place;
<as>as, <ex>sons</ex> of Albion; <ex>sons</ex> of New
England</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The produce of anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Earth's tall <qex>sons</qex>, the cedar, oak, and pine.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackmore.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> (Commonly with the def. article) <def>Jesus Christ, the
Savior; -- called the <xex>Son</xex> of God, and the <xex>Son</xex> of
man.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We . . . do testify that the Father sent the <qex>Son</qex> to be
the Savior of the world.</q> <rj><qau>1 John iv. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who gave His <qex>Son</qex> sure all has given.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The expressions <xex>son of pride</xex>, <xex>sons of
light</xex>, <xex>son of Belial</xex>, are Hebraisms, which denote
persons possessing the qualitites of pride, of light, or of Belial, as
children inherit the qualities of their ancestors.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sons of the prophets</b></col>. <cd>See <xex>School of
the prophets</xex>, under <er>Prophet</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sonance</ent>⟦br⟧
